[[Judith Reeves-Stevens|Judith]] and [[Garfield Reeves-Stevens]] provide the backstory of the extremely sadistic droid [[EV-9D9/Legends|EV-9D9]] in their co-written short story "'''A Bad Feeling: The Tale of EV-9D9'''". The story appeared in ''[[Tales from Jabba's Palace]]'', published [[December]] [[1995]] by [[Bantam Spectra]].

==Plot summary==
The sadistic [[EV-series supervisor droid/Legends|droid]] [[EV-9D9/Legends|EV-9D9]] breaks free from the detention area of [[Cloud City/Legends|Cloud City]]. [[Baron Administrator/Legends|Baron Administrator]] [[Lando Calrissian/Legends|Lando Calrissian]] tries to prevent her escape with help from his aide [[Lobot/Legends|Lobot]], the [[Security officer/Legends|security officer]] [[Sarl Random]], and a [[12-4C-41 traffic control droid|traffic droid]] designated [[12-4C-41]]. They fail, and EV-9D9 escapes on the ''[[Iopene Princess]]'', leaving a swath of mechanical mayhem in her wake.

[[Standard year/Legends|Years]] later, EV-9D9 is working as [[Jabba Desilijic Tiure/Legends|Jabba's]] [[Droid/Legends|droid]] supervisor, delighting in [[Torture/Legends|torturing]] her subjects and modifying them with devices to ensure they feel pain. Two new droids, [[R2-D2/Legends|R2-D2]] and [[C-3PO/Legends|C-3PO]], are brought to her and she gives them assignments. After they leave, she becomes suspicious. She eventually discovers that Lando Calrissian has infiltrated the [[Jabba's Palace/Legends|palace]] under the pseudonym [[Lando Calrissian/Legends|Tamtel Skreej]]. She assumes that the droids are part of a plot of Lando's to recapture her. She plans to cover her tracks and leave [[Tatooine/Legends|Tatooine]], but is attacked by an unknown figure. She assumes it is Lando, but it turns out to be 12-4C-41, seeking vengeance for the torture and destruction of his "brothers" on Cloud City. 12-4C-41 releases the mangled droids that EV-9D9 has tortured so they can take revenge on her, tearing her apart. He also removes her [[Pain simulator|pain simulator]], so she cannot take twisted pleasure from her own destruction.

==Continuity==
The [[12-4C-41 traffic control droid|droid]] [[12-4C-41]]'s name is a reference to a [[Wikipedia: 1911|1911]] science fiction novel by [[Wikipedia: Hugo Gernsback|Hugo Gernsback]], [[Wikipedia: Amazing Stories Quaterly|''Ralph 124C 41+'']], an alphanumeric pun meaning "one to foresee for one." Measuring all fictional accounts as equal, this is the ''third'' time the [[Star Wars Legends|Expanded Universe]] has jeopardized [[Cloud City/Legends|Cloud City]] with wide-scale destruction during [[Lando Calrissian/Legends|Lando's]] tenure as [[Baron Administrator/Legends|baron administrator]]. In the [[Star Wars (1977)|Marvel Comic series]], [[Ugnaught/Legends|Ugnaught]] insurrectionists detonate [[Explosive charge/Legends|explosives]] that cause the city's [[Antigrav/Legends|antigravity]] generators to sputter in ''Coffin in the Clouds,'' [[Star Wars (1977) 56|Star Wars #56]] ([[1982]]). In the roleplaying game module [[Crisis on Cloud City (adventure book)|''Crisis on Cloud City'']] ([[1989]]), the [[Droid/Legends|droid]] intelligence [[X0-X1]] nearly succeeds with a mechanical coup that remarkably resembles [[EV-9D9/Legends|Ninedenine's]] botched usurpation.<ref name="TERC" />

